## üéØ Clinical Applications

### Primary Pattern & Manifestations
**Pattern**: Spleen qi deficiency
**Key Symptoms**: Fatigue, weak voice, poor appetite, loose stools, abdominal distension after eating, pale complexion, shortness of breath
**Tongue**: Pale, often with tooth marks, thin white coating
**Pulse**: Weak, especially in the middle position (spleen/stomach)

### Secondary Applications
- Chronic digestive weakness
- Post-illness recovery with qi deficiency
- Chronic diarrhea from spleen deficiency
- Poor appetite in children or elderly
- Chronic fatigue with digestive component
- Immune deficiency with digestive weakness

### Modern Clinical Uses
- Functional dyspepsia with qi deficiency
- Chronic fatigue syndrome with digestive symptoms
- Post-chemotherapy digestive recovery
- Chronic diarrhea or loose stools
- Poor appetite and malnutrition
- Immune deficiency conditions

## üìù Therapeutic Actions
**Primary**: Tonify qi, strengthen spleen, harmonize middle jiao

**Secondary**: Transform dampness, stop diarrhea, improve appetite, boost immunity

## üîÑ Modifications & Variations

### Common Additions
| Condition | Add Herbs | Rationale |
|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| With dampness/phlegm | Chen Pi + Ban Xia | Transform phlegm, regulate qi |
